ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

MJ5: Has there ever been a period of a month or more when a great deal of your time was spent using marijuana, getting marijuana, or getting over its effects?

MJ6.1: Because of your marijuana use, did you ever experience any of the following? - feeling depressed or uninterested in things for more than 24 hours to the point that it interfered with your functioning?

MJ6.2: Because of your marijuana use, did you ever experience any of the following? - having trouble concentrating or having such trouble thinking clearly for more than 24 hours that it interfered with your functioning?

MJ6.3: Because of your marijuana use, did you ever experience any of the following? - feeling paranoid or suspicious of people for more than 24 hours to the point that it interfered with your relationships?
MJ6.4: Because of your marijuana use, did you ever experience any of the following? - decreased contact with friends or family?
MJ6.5: Because of your marijuana use, did you ever experience any of the following? - hearing, seeing, or smelling things that were not really there?
MJ6a1: Did you continue to use marijuana after you knew it caused this? - feeling depressed or uninterested in things for more than 24 hours to the point that it interfered with your functioning?

MJ6a2: Did you continue to use marijuana after you knew it caused this? - having trouble concentrating or having such trouble thinking clearly for more than 24 hours that it interfered with your functioning?
MJ6a3: Did you continue to use marijuana after you knew it caused this? - feeling paranoid or suspicious of people for more than 24 hours to the point that it interfered with your relationships?
MJ6a4: Did you continue to use marijuana after you knew it caused this? - decreased contact with friends or family?
MJ6a5: Did you continue to use marijuana after you knew it caused this? - hearing, seeing, or smelling things that were not really there?
MJ6b: Did you have decreased contact with friends or family 3 or more times in any 12-month period?
MJ7: Have you often wanted to stop or cut down on marijuana?
MJ7a: Have you ever tried to stop or cut down on marijuana but found you could not? IF NEVER TRIED TO STOP/CUT DOWN, CODE NO.
MJ7B: Were you unable to stop or cut down 3 or more times?
MJ8: Have you often used marijuana more frequently or in larger amounts than you intended to?
MJ9: Did you ever need larger amounts of marijuana to get an effect, or did you ever find that you could no longer get high on the amount you used to use?

MJ10.1: When you stopped, cut down, or went without marijuana, did you ever experience any of these following problems for most of the day for 2 days or longer? - Did you feel nervous, tense, restless or irritable?
MJ10.2: When you stopped, cut down, or went without marijuana, did you ever experience any of these following problems for most of the day for 2 days or longer? - Did you have trouble sleeping?
MJ10.3: When you stopped, cut down, or went without marijuana, did you ever experience any of these following problems for most of the day for 2 days or longer? - Did you tremble or twitch?
MJ10.4: When you stopped, cut down, or went without marijuana, did you ever experience any of these following problems for most of the day for 2 days or longer? - Did you sweat or have a fever?
MJ10.5: When you stopped, cut down, or went without marijuana, did you ever experience any of these following problems for most of the day for 2 days or longer? - Did you have nausea or vomiting?

MJ10.6: When you stopped, cut down, or went without marijuana, did you ever experience any of these following problems for most of the day for 2 days or longer? - Did you have diarrhea or stomach aches?

MJ10.7: When you stopped, cut down, or went without marijuana, did you ever experience any of these following problems for most of the day for 2 days or longer? - Did you have a marked increase or decrease in appetite, that is, have a significant change from your normal level?
MJ10a: Have you ever used marijuana to keep from having any of these problems or to make them go away?
MJ10b: Have you ever used marijuana 3 or more times to keep from having any of these problems or to make them go away?
MJ10c: Did these problems ever occur together?
MJ10d.1: Which problems occurred together? - You felt nervous, tense, restless or irritable?
MJ10d.2: Which problems occurred together? - You had trouble sleeping?
MJ10d.3: Which problems occurred together? - You trembled or twitched?
MJ10d.4: Which problems occurred together? - You experienced sweating or had a fever?
MJ10d.5: Which problems occurred together? - You had nausea or vomiting?
MJ10d.6: Which problems occurred together? - You had diarrhea or stomach aches?
MJ10d.7: Which problems occurred together? - You had a marked change in appetite?
MJ10e: How many times did you have problems like that (when they occurred together)?
MJ10f: What was the longest time these problems occurred together? (Answer given In days)
MJ10g: Did these problems interfere with your functioning at work, school, or home?

MJ11: Have you ever been under the effects of marijuana when it increased your chances of getting hurt, for instance, when driving a car or boat, using knives, machinery or guns, crossing against traffic, climbing or swimming?
MJ11a: Have you been in situations where you are under the effects of marijuana when it increased your chances of getting hurt, 3 or more times?
MJ11a1: Have you been in situations where you are under the effects of marijuana when it increased your chances of getting hurt, 3 or more times in any 12-month period?
MJ11b: Did marijuana ever cause you to have any accidental injuries like a bad fall, cutting or burning yourself, or being hurt in a traffic accident?
MJ11c: Did marijuana ever cause you to have any accidental injuries like a bad fall, cutting or burning yourself, or being hurt in a traffic accident, 3 or more times?
MJ11c1: Did marijuana ever cause you to have any accidental injuries like a bad fall, cutting or burning yourself, or being hurt in a traffic accident, 3 or more times in any 12-month period?

MJ12b: Did you continue to use marijuana after you realized it was causing problems with your friends or family?

MJ13a1: Have you ever been arrested or had any other trouble with the police because of your marijuana use, 3 or more times in any 12-month period?

MJ14a: Has your being high on marijuana or experiencing its after-effects often interfered with your work, school, household, or child care responsibilities, 3 or more times in any 12-month period?

SU1:  IF DP15B=5, SKIP TO SU1A.  Now I am going to ask you some (further) questions about suicide. Have you ever thought about killing yourself?
SU1a: Earlier you told me that you would thought about taking your own life, did those thoughts persist for at least 7 days in a row?
SU1b: IF DP15C=5, SKIP TO SU1C. Did you have a plan? (Did you actually consider a way to take your life?)
SU1c: Earlier you told me you had a plan for taking your own life, what were you going to do? SPECIFY
SU_ao1: How old were you the very first time you had these thoughts about taking your own life?
SU_ar1: How old were you when you last had these thoughts about taking your own life?
SU_r1: Did you have these thoughts about taking your own life within the last 30 days?
SU2: IF DP15D=5, SKIP TO SU2A. Have you ever tried to kill yourself?
SU2a: Earlier you said that you would tried to kill yourself, how many times did you try to kill yourself?
SU_ao2: How old were you the first time you tried to kill yourself?
SU_o2: The first time you tried to kill yourself, was it within the last 30 days?
SU_ar2: How old were you the last time you tried to kill yourself?
SU_r2: The last time you tried to kill yourself, was it within the last 30 days?
SU3: How did you try to kill yourself? IF MORE THAN 1, ASK ABOUT THE MOST SERIOUS ATTEMPT. CODE SILENTLY: TYPE OF METHOD INTENDED
Notes: 1=Fire gun; 2=Crash car; 3=Carbon monoxide poisoning; 4=Cut wrists or stab self; 5=Take pills; 6=Jump from height; 7=Jump in front of train/car/vehicle; 8=Strangulation, choking, suffocation, hanging, drowning; 9=Other or combination

ElementDescription: SU3a: How close did you come to killing yourself? CODE SILENTLY: DEGREE OF COMPLETION.
Notes: 2=Put self in vicinity (e.g., brought gun/pills into room, walked into train station); 3=Stopped short of completing act (held gun/pills, stood on edge of platform, sat in car); 4=Attempted act (jumped, pulled trigger, swallowed pills)

ElementDescription: SU3b: Did you really want to die when trying to kill yourself?
SU3c: CODE SILENTLY: Measure patient's INTENT to kill themselves
Notes: 1=Unclear (no information or not sure); 2=Denies intent; 3=Reports minimal intent; 4=Reports significant intent with some ambivalence; 5=Very severe/extreme intent to die

AG1: Some people have a fear of being in certain places or situations where they feel it would be difficult to leave easily. Some situations like this include being alone away from home; being in a crowd; being in a place where there was a long distance between exits, like in a tunnel or on a bridge; traveling in a bus, car, or train; or being in an elevator.
